      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And gave . . . of gold.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—And they gave . . . gold, five thousand talents; between thirty and forty millions sterling (!).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ten thousand drams.—Rather, Darics. The Daric (Greek, Δαρεικὸς) was a Persian gold coin, value about £1 2s., first struck by the great Darius, son of Hystaspes (B.C. 521-485). It remained current in Western Asia long after the fall of the Persian Empire. The Hebrew word (’ădarkônîm) occurs again only once, viz., at Ezra 8:27, where it clearly means Darics, and is so rendered by the Syriac (dărîkûnê). The darkôn (or darbôn) is mentioned in the Talmud as a Persian coin. The chronicler, or his authority, has evidently substituted a familiar modern term for some ancient expression of value. No real coins are mentioned in Scripture before the age of the exile.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Ten thousand drams.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Rather, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Darics.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The Daric (Greek, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "greekheb",
            "text": "Δαρεικὸς",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
